liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The navy has recorded the highest number of sexual assaults in Australia's Defence force, in a new report released by the Director of Military Prosecutions. AAP reports that the documents reveal there were 47 sexual assault and related offences received by the office last year, up from 30 in 2021. Despite being a smaller service than the army, there were 21 sexual offences received from the navy last year (up from 12 in 2021), with 18 offences in the army (up from right in 2021) and eight in the air force (down from 10 in 2021). Sexual assault support lines: 1800 Respect National Helpline : 1800 737 732 Sexual Assault Crisis Line Victoria : 1800 806 292 Safe Steps Crisis Line (Vic) : 1800 015 188 Men's Referral Service : 1300 766 491 Lifeline (24-hour crisis line): 131 114 Victims of Crime Helpline : 1800 819 817

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Karen Williams, mayor of Redland City Council, is speaking on ABC News about the Russell Island blaze which killed a father and his five sons over the weekend. She says the tragedy will resonate with the community for quite some time. "Which is why Redland City Council spent most of yesterday making sure that we've got the appropriate resources on the island and on the mainland to wrap around the community and those people who are first responders or have been impacted by this tragic event," she says. Disaster chaplains and community support are made available to residents and a space has been set up for people who want to pay their respects or need assistance. Williams says the island, which is home to about 3,500 people, is a very small and tight-knit community. "Everybody knows everybody and, at the same time, they're all there to make sure that they support each other," she says. "I just think they are still reeling at this whole event. It's so tragic."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Queensland's Russell Island community grieving after deadly house fire, mayor says

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Syrian state media says an Israeli missile attack on Syria's capital Damascus has killed four soldiers, wounded four more and caused "some material damage". "At about 2:20 in the morning today, the Israeli enemy launched an aerial aggression from the direction of the occupied Syrian Golan Heights, targeting some points in the vicinity of the city of Damascus," a military source reportedly says. Syrian air defences intercepted the Israeli missiles and shot down some of them, the source added. Israel has for years carried out attacks against what it has described as Iran-linked targets in Syria, where Iran's influence has grown since it began supporting President Bashar al-Assad in the civil war that started in 2011. Reporting by Reuters

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Australian share market has shown little sign of shifting from its early trajectory, with the benchmark ASX 200 index still down 0.3% at 7,304 points around 1:45pm AEST. Industrials and healthcare are still leading the losses, with the big banking and mining sectors also in the red. Real estate, utilities, energy and consumer cyclicals are the only sectors in the black, with 104 stocks trading down to 87 gaining ground among the top 200. Some smaller miners, particularly in the renewable energy/electronics areas of lithium and rare earths, were making the biggest gains. Meanwhile, buy now pay later and payments services firm Block was dominating the falls, down 11.3% to $97.13 as investors remained disappointed by a quarterly trading update delivered at the end of last week. Australian medical device makers Resmed and Nanosonics also on the nose, off 4.6 and 4.1% respectively.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Market showing few signs of change as ASX heads towards modest losses

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Hello – Rachel Pupazzoni jumping in with an update from WA where the Diggers and Dealers Mining Conference is being held in Kalgoorlie. This event attracts thousands of people in and linked to the resources sector from Australia and around the globe. Deloitte has crunched some numbers about WA-listed companies on the ASX – finding the WA Index outperformed the broader ASX 200 through FY 23. It ended the financial year up 21 per cent, with a combined value of $363.3 billion. The vast majority of that comes down to the mining sector. Even though commodity prices broadly are off their peaks, there's still growth in some company spreadsheets. "The index performance this year comes unphased by the broader commodity markets which did it tough," said Deloitte Western Australia Audit & Assurance partner Dave Andrews. "Pockets of optimism in uranium, gold, lead and tin were outweighed by significant price retractions across many of the commodities surveyed. " "It is clear that battery-based solutions are critical to the electrification of vehicles and general mobility and it's no surprise battery technologies, EVs and lithium stocks are the talk around town, " Mr Andrews added. Here are Deloitte's Top Three movers in the WA Index Top 20 for the year ended 30 June 2023: Liontown Resources – market capitalisation up 169.5% to $6.2bn Pilbara Minerals – market capitalisation up 115.1% to $14.7bn De Grey Mining – market capitalisation up 85.1% to $2.1bn I'll be here in Kalgoorlie all week. Tonight on The Business I sit down with Pilbara Minerals boss Dale Henderson. With the lithium price falling, and Pilbara Minerals announcing expansion plans, it'll make for an interesting conversation.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Miners drive strength among WA-listed companies

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: While there are signs inflation is slowing down, and few signs of wages growth seriously accelerating, fresh job ads data appears to show the labour market in robust health. The ANZ-Indeed job ads index rose 0.4% in July. That was after a downwardly revised 2.7% slump in June. However, despite the trend being in decline for job ads, Indeed's Asia-Pacific economist Callam Pickering says demand for labour remains robust. "Despite a more challenging economic environment, job creation remains exceptionally strong," he wrote. "ANZ-Indeed Job Ads are around 50% above pre-pandemic levels. "Quite simply, there is still an incredible number of jobs available across the nation. Certainly enough to absorb high immigration and keep unemployment low." "Australia's labour market remains tight with the unemployment rate 3.5% and just 1.2 unemployed people per job vacancy nationwide, compared to 3.1 unemployed people before the pandemic. "Talent and skill-shortages remain widespread and recruitment challenges are among the biggest impediments for businesses looking to expand." The jobs market is one factor that is still keeping another potential interest rate rise on the table. Although some economists who worked through the last non-pandemic recession in Australia warn that the jobs market often looks fine early in an economic downturn, until it suddenly deteriorates. #ICYMI last week, Alicia Barry's interview with NAB chief economist Alan Oster is well worth watching.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Job ads remain 50 per cent above pre-pandemic levels
